{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "The measurement of the \u03c3(e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 ) cross section allows to determine the pion form factor |F \u03c0 | 2 and the two pion contribution to the muon anomaly a \u00b5 . ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "Such a measurement has been performed with the KLOE detector at DA\u03a6N E, the Frascati \u03c6-factory. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The preliminary results on the combination of the last analysis (KLOE12) with two previous published (KLOE08, KLOE10) will be presented in the following.",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The anomalous magnetic moment of the muon defined as a \u00b5 \u2261 g\u00b5\u22122 2 , can be accurately measured and, within the SM framework, precisely predicted [1]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 145,
                    "end": 148,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The experimental value of a \u00b5 ((11659208.9 \u00b1 6.3) \u00d7 10 \u221210 ) measured at the Brookhaven Laboratory differs from the SM estimates by 3.2 -3.6 \u03c3 [2]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 143,
                    "end": 146,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "If the deviation is confirmed with higher precision it would signal of new physics.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The main theoretical uncertainty for a \u00b5 comes from hadronic contributions. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The leading order hadronic term can be derived from a combination of experimental cross section data, related to e + e \u2212 annihilation to hadrons.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "At DA\u03a6N E the differential cross section (as a function of m \u03c0\u03c0 ) for the e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3 initial state radiation (ISR) process is measured. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 3,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "DA\u00ce\u00a6N",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Then, the dipion cross section \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 \u2261 \u03c3(e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 ) has been obtained from:",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "where the radiator function H is computed from QED with complete NLO corrections and depends on the initial e + e \u2212 center of mass energy (1) arXiv:1501.04446v1 [hep-ex] 19 Jan 2015 squared s. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 138,
                    "end": 141,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "(1)"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The dipion cross section \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 obtained from Eq. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "1 requires the correction for final state radiation (FSR). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Eq. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "1 is also valid for the e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u00b5 + \u00b5 \u2212 \u03b3 and e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u00b5 + \u00b5 \u2212 processes with the same radiator function H. Thus, we can determine \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 from the ratio of the \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3 and \u00b5 + \u00b5 \u2212 \u03b3 differential cross sections for the same value of the dipion and dimuon invariant mass. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The pion form factor can then be determined using the following equation:",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "where \u03b4 V P is the Vacuum Polarization (VP) correction , \u03b7 \u03c0 accounts for the FSR radiation assuming point-like pions. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "\u03c3 0 \u03c0\u03c0 is a bare cross section, i.e. corrected for the running of \u03b1 em and inclusive of FSR, defined as [6] \u03c3",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 104,
                    "end": 107,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "where",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Many radiative corrections drop out for this ratio method: contributions due to the radiator function (this allows to suppress the related systematic uncertainty of 0.5% for the direct \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 measurement), to the integrated luminosity (since the data for the \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3 and \u00b5 + \u00b5 \u2212 \u03b3 processes are collected simultaneously) and finally to the vacuum polarization.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "2. Measurement of the e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 cross section at KLOE",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In the 2008 and 2010 two analyses of the \u03c3(e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3) have been performed at DA\u03a6N E with the KLOE detector. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "A cross section of the detector in the y, z plane is shown in Fig.1. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 62,
                    "end": 67,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig.1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The KLOE08 analysis [7] used a data sample corresponding to an integrated luminosity of 240 pb \u22121 collected at \u221a s = m \u03c6 in 2002 and selection cuts in which the photon is emitted within a cone of \u03b8 \u03b3 < 15 \u2022 around the beamline (narrow cones in Fig.1) and the two charged pion tracks have 50 \u2022 < \u03b8 \u03c0 < 130 \u2022 (wide cones in Fig. 1). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 20,
                    "end": 23,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[7]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 244,
                    "end": 249,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig.1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 322,
                    "end": 328,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In this configuration, the photon is not detected and the photon momentum is reconstructed from missing momentum: p \u03b3 p miss = \u2212( p + + p \u2212 ). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "These selection cuts provide high statistics data sample for the ISR signal events, and significantly reduce contamination from the resonant process e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c6 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03c0 0 .",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "From the bare cross section, the dipion contribution to the muon anomaly \u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 is measured:",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 (0.592 < M \u03c0\u03c0 < 0.975GeV ) = (387.2 \u00b1 3.3) \u00d7 10 \u221210 . ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The KLOE10 analysis [8] was performed requiring events that are selected to have a photon at large polar angles between 50 \u2022 < \u03b8 \u03b3 < 130 \u2022 (wide cones in Fig.1), in the same angular region as the pions. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 20,
                    "end": 23,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[8]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 154,
                    "end": 159,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig.1"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 8,
                    "end": 11,
                    "type": "version",
                    "rawForm": "10",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "#software-simple-s1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This selection allow to access the two pion threshold. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "However, compared to the measurement with photons at small angles, this condition reduces statistics and increases the background from the process \u03c6 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03c0 0 . ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The dispersion integral for \u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 is computed as the sum of the values for \u03c3 0 \u03c0\u03c0(\u03b3) times the kernel K(s), times \u2206s = 0.01GeV 2",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The following value for the dipion contribution to the muon anomaly \u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 was found:",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 (0.1 \u2212 0.85)GeV 2 = (478.5 \u00b1 2.0 stat \u00b1 5.0 exp \u00b1 4.5 th ) \u00d7 10 \u221210 . ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The last KLOE measurement of the e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 cross section (KLOE12) has been obtained from the ratio between the pion and muon ISR differential cross section. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The data sample is the same as for the KLOE08 analysis. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The separation between the \u03c0\u03c0\u03b3 and \u00b5\u00b5\u03b3 events is obtained assuming the final state with two charged particles with equal mass M T RK and one photon. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The M T RK < 115M eV identifies the muons and M T RK > 130M eV the pions.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The selection procedure has been compared to other techniques, such as a kinematic fit or applying a quality cut on the helix fit for both tracks, all leading to consistent results. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Trigger, particle identification and tracking efficiencies have been checked using control data samples. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The differential \u00b5\u00b5\u03b3 cross section is obtained from the observed event count N obs and background estimate N bkg , as:",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "where L is the integrated luminosity from Ref. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "[9] and (s \u00b5 ) the selection efficiency. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[9]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The bare cross section \u03c3 0 \u03c0\u03c0(\u03b3) (inclusive of FSR, with VP effects removed) is obtained from the bin-by-bin ratio of the KLOE08 \u03c0\u03c0\u03b3 and the described above \u00b5\u00b5\u03b3 differential cross sections. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The bare cross section is used in the dispersion integral to compute \u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 . ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The pion form factor |F \u03c0 | 2 is extracted using Eq. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "(2). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Eq. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "4 gives \u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 = (385.1 \u00b1 1.1 stat \u00b1 2.6 exp \u00b1 0.8 th ) \u00d7 10 \u221210 in the interval 0.35 < M 2 \u03c0\u03c0 < 0.95GeV 2 . ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "For each bin contributing to the integral, statistical errors are combined in quadrature and systematic errors are added linearly. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The last three KLOE estimations on the \u2206 \u03c0\u03c0 a \u00b5 (KLOE08, KLOE10, KLOE12) have been compared and are consistent (as you can see in the table 1). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The preliminary combination of these KLOE results is reported in the figure 2 [10]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 78,
                    "end": 82,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It is obtained using the Best Linear Unbiased Estimate (BLUE ) method [11,12]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 70,
                    "end": 74,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "[11,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 74,
                    "end": 77,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In the Fig. 2 (left) the pion form factor measurements for the three KLOE analysis and the fractional difference (right) are shown [10]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 7,
                    "end": 13,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 131,
                    "end": 135,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The cross section ratio method used in the KLOE12 measurement reduces significantly the theoretical and the systematic error.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The following a \u00b5 \u03c0\u03c0 values are found: ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Conclusion",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Precision measurements of the pion vector form factor using the Initial State Radiation (ISR) have been performed by the KLOE/KLOE-2 Collaboration during the last 10 years. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The preliminary consolidation of the",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "|F BLU E | 2 Fig. 2. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 13,
                    "end": 19,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Preliminary combination of the last three KLOE results (KLOE08, KLOE10, KLOE12) on the pion form factor measurements (left) and the fractional difference (right) using the Best Linear Unbiased Estimate (BLUE ) method [11,12]. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 217,
                    "end": 221,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "[11,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 221,
                    "end": 224,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The light blue band in the fractional difference is the statistical error and the dark blue band is the combined statistical and systematic uncertainty [10].",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 152,
                    "end": 156,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "last analysis (KLOE12) with two previously published (KLOE08, KLOE10) ones has been presented. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The result confirms the current discrepancy (\u223c 3\u03c3) between the Standard Model (SM) calculation and the experimental value of the muon anomaly a \u00b5 measured at BNL. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "In the near future the \u03b3\u03b3 Physics program of the KLOE-2 experiment [13] will further shed light in this field, with e.g. the study of the radiative width of pseudoscalar mesons and of the transition form factors [14], thanks to the luminosity upgrade of DA\u03c6NE and the KLOE upgrade with the addition of new detectors: low energy [15] and high energy [16] e + e \u2212 taggers, an inner tracker [17], crystal calorimeters (CCALT) [18], and tile calorimeters (QCALT) [19].",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
